I.    Introduction

A Risk Management Program has been implemented at the Menasha Packaging Company (Menasha), Bolingbrook facility, for the reduction of accidental releases of hazardous materials. This Program summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that work together to minimize the risk to site personnel, contractors, visitors, and the community and environment at large of hazardous chemical releases. The Risk Management Plan (RMP) is organized to correspond with specific U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) RMP, Program 3 of 40 CFR 68, definitions and requirements of Subpart G, including: 

?    Introduction;

?    Menasha's policies to protect health, environment, and safety;

?    Facility identification and regulated substances covered processes;

?    Hazard Assessment;

?    Prevention Program;

?    Five-Year Accident History;

?    Emergency Response Plan; 

?    Emergency Communications;

?    Spill Reporting / Environmental Release Procedures;

?    Planned changes to improve safety; and

?    Management Program



II.    Menasha's Policies To Protect Health, Environment, and Safety

Risk management and safety are important concerns at Menasha; this RMP formalizes and documents these activities. Menasha is committed to conducting its operations in a safe and responsible manner and to reducing risks to human health and to the environment. It is Menasha policy to comply with all applicable federal, state, and local rules and regulations. 



This RMP has identified potential hazards and has taken steps to design and maintain a safe facility in order to prevent releases, and minimize the consequences of accidental releases, which could occur. This RMP addresses potentially catastrophic chemical releases that could result in immediate harm and acute health effects to offsite receptors (public and environmental). Menasha has developed an Emergency Action Plan that contains procedures designed to maximize the safety of all employees, contractors, and
